# 4. Stacking
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import StackingRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score


# Define the base models
base_models = [
    ('lightgbm', lightgbm_model),
    ('xgboost', xgboost_model)  # Fixed missing comm
]

# Define the meta-model (Linear Regression)
meta_model = LinearRegression()

# Create the stacking model
stacking_model = StackingRegressor(estimators=base_models, final_estimator=meta_model, cv=5)

# Train the stacking model
print("Training Stacking Model with Linear Regression as Meta-Model...")
stacking_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training set
y_train_pred = stacking_model.predict(X_train)

# Evaluate the model on the training set
train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

print("Training Set Performance:")
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", train_mae)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", train_mse)
print(f"RMSE: {train_rmse:.4f}")
print("R² Score:", train_r2)

print("-----------------------------------------------")

# Make predictions on the test set
y_test_pred = stacking_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model on the test set
test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

print("\nTest Set Performance:")
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", test_mae)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", test_mse)
print(f"RMSE: {test_rmse:.4f}")
print("R² Score:", test_r2)

Overfitting: Random Forest and XGBoost show signs of overfitting, with excellent training performance but degraded test performance.

# Randomised search CV

# 1. LightGBM

# Define the model
lgbm = lgb.LGBMRegressor()

# Define the hyperparameter grid
param_dist = {
    'max_bin': [255, 512, 1024],
    'num_leaves': np.arange(20, 200, 10),
    'max_depth': np.arange(3, 12),
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1],
    'n_estimators': np.arange(100, 1000, 100),
    'min_data_in_leaf': [20, 50, 100],
    'min_sum_hessian_in_leaf': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1],
    'bagging_fraction': [0.8, 0.9],
    'bagging_freq': [5, 10],
    'feature_fraction': [0.8, 0.9],
    'lambda_l1': [0, 0.1, 0.2],
    'lambda_l2': [0, 0.1, 0.2],
    'min_gain_to_split': [0, 0.1, 0.2],
    'path_smooth': [0, 0.1, 0.2],
    'boosting_type': ['gbdt', 'dart']
}

# Randomized Search
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=lgbm,
    param_distributions=param_dist,
    n_iter=50,  
    scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',  
    cv=5, 
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1  
)

# Fit the model
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters and score
print("Best Parameters:", random_search.best_params_)
print("Best Score (Negative MSE):", random_search.best_score_)

# 2. Xgboost model
# Define the model
xgb = XGBRegressor()

# Define the hyperparameter grid
param_dist = {
    'max_depth': np.arange(3, 10),
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2],
    'n_estimators': np.arange(100, 1000, 100),
    'subsample': [0.7, 0.8, 0.9],
    'colsample_bytree': [0.7, 0.8, 0.9],
    'gamma': [0, 0.1, 0.2],
    'reg_alpha': [0, 0.1, 1, 10],  # L1 regularization
    'reg_lambda': [0, 0.1, 1, 10],  # L2 regularization
    'min_child_weight': [1, 5, 10]
}

# Randomized Search
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb,
    param_distributions=param_dist,
    n_iter=50,  # Number of parameter settings to sample
    scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',  # Use MSE as the evaluation metric
    cv=5,  # 5-fold cross-validation
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1  # Use all available cores
)

# Fit the model
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters and score
print("Best Parameters:", random_search.best_params_)
print("Best Score (Negative MSE):", random_search.best_score_)

3. Stacked model¶

# creating a hybrid model of the two models
# 4. Stacking
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import StackingRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score


# Define the base models
base_models = [
    ('lightgbm', lgbm_optimal),
    ('xgboost', xgb_optimal) 
]

# Define the meta-model (Linear Regression)
meta_model = LinearRegression()

# Create the stacking model
stacking_model_opt = StackingRegressor(estimators=base_models, final_estimator=meta_model, cv=5)

# Train the stacking model
print("Training Stacking Model with Linear Regression as Meta-Model...")
stacking_model_opt.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the training set
y_train_pred = stacking_model_opt.predict(X_train)

# Evaluate the model on the training set
train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

print("Training Set Performance:")
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", train_mae)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", train_mse)
print(f"RMSE: {train_rmse:.4f}")
print("R² Score:", train_r2)

print("-----------------------------------------------")

# Make predictions on the test set
y_test_pred = stacking_model_opt.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model on the test set
test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

print("\nTest Set Performance:")
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", test_mae)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", test_mse)
print(f"RMSE: {test_rmse:.4f}")
print("R² Score:", test_r2)

Stacked Model is the best overall:

  • It achieves the best test set performance (lowest MAE, lowest RMSE, and highest R²).

  • It generalizes well, with the smallest gap between training and test performance.

  • It leverages the strengths of multiple models, making it more robust and reliable.

Runner-Up:

  • LightGBM is a close second:

  • It performs slightly better than XGBoost on both training and test sets.

  • It is simpler and faster to train compared to the Stacked Model.

Third Place: XGBoost:

  • It performs well but is slightly worse than LightGBM and the Stacked Model.

  • It may require more tuning to match the performance of the other two models.

1. LightGBM¶

In [18]:

shap_values_lgbm = explainer_lgbm(X_test)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
shap.summary_plot(shap_values_lgbm, X_test)
plt.show()

Insights:

  • Time-series features (Lag_1, Lag_2, Lag_3, etc.) are the most important predictors, showing PM2.5 levels depend significantly on past values.

  • Wind speed has a notable impact, with higher wind speeds reducing PM2.5 (negative SHAP values for high wind speed).

  • Meteorological variables like temperature, dew point, and pressure have a minor influence, meaning weather conditions alone may not be strong predictors of PM2.5 without considering past PM2.5 values.

  • Hour and Week also affect PM2.5, suggesting a seasonal or diurnal pattern (possibly due to traffic, industry activity, or meteorological variations).

lag_1 dominatedmeaning recent historical values are key predictors.

Environmental conditions such as pressure and wind_deg can boost or moderate predictions, depending on the context.

Wind speed and hour of the day are important negative influencers, possibly tied to cooling, turbulence, or time-based cycles.

Temporal features (year, week) again show consistent but small positive impacts, indicating trends or seasonal effects.

Testing the model on the unseen data¶

In [26]:
# Testing LightGBM model on unseen data
# Make predictions on the final evaluation set
y_val_pred = stacking_model_opt.predict(X_val)

# Evaluate the model on the final evaluation set
final_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_val_pred)
final_mse = mean_squared_error(y_val, y_val_pred)
final_rmse = np.sqrt(final_mse)
final_r2 = r2_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

# Print the final evaluation metrics
print("Final Evaluation Set Performance:")
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", final_mae)
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", final_mse)
print(f"RMSE: {final_rmse:.4f}")
print("R² Score:", final_r2)

Saving the best model¶

In [32]:
models = {
    "Stacking_Model": stacking_model_opt,
    "XGBoost": xgb_optimal,
    "LightGBM": lgbm_optimal
}

model_results = []

for model_name, model in models.items():
    # Get predictions
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Calculate metrics
    train_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred))
    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

    test_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred))
    test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
    test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

    # Feature importance (if available)
    feature_importance = None
    if hasattr(model, 'feature_importances_'):
        feature_importance = dict(zip(X_train.columns, model.feature_importances_))
    elif hasattr(model, 'coef_'):  # For linear models
        feature_importance = dict(zip(X_train.columns, model.coef_))

    # Store results
    model_results.append({
        'model_name': model_name,
        'training_metrics': {
            'rmse': train_rmse,
            'mae': train_mae,
            'r2': train_r2
        },
        'test_metrics': {
            'rmse': test_rmse,
            'mae': test_mae,
            'r2': test_r2
        },
        'feature_importance': feature_importance
    })
